+{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"api_error_status":null,"duration_ms":303743,"duration_api_ms":301899,"ttft_ms":2937,"num_turns":19,"result":"Build is green (only a pre-existing warning). Per instructions, I won't re-run the test — the mega-loop will re-test.\n\n**Root cause:** Three locations in `crates/lua-vm/src/vm.rs` mishandle upvalue closing on return relative to the C reference (`reference/lua-c/lvm.c:1716-1775`):\n\n1. `OpCode::Return` (vm.rs:2207) called `close_upvals(base)` unconditionally and *before* the top-adjustment, but C only calls it inside `if (TESTARG_k(i))` and after setting `L->top.p = ci->top.p`.\n2. `OpCode::Return0` (vm.rs:2242) called `close_upvals(base)`, but C never closes here.\n3. `OpCode::Return1` (vm.rs:2264) — same bug; this was the panic site.\n\nThe codegen's `cg_finish` (lua-parse/src/lib.rs:1790) already upgrades `RETURN0/RETURN1 → RETURN+k` when `needclose` is set, so executing `RETURN0/RETURN1` should never need a close. With Rust's incorrect closure-close ordering, it tried to close an upvalue at idx 13 with `top=12`, tripping the invariant `uplevel(uv) < L->top.p`.\n\n**Fix:** Moved `close_upvals(base)` inside `if i.test_k()` and after `set_top(ci_top)` in `OP_RETURN`; removed the spurious `close_upvals` call from `OP_RETURN0` and `OP_RETURN1`. Also removed the diagnostic `eprintln!` from `func.rs`.\n\n**New state:** Build green. Did not re-test (mega-loop will verify).","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"bad5d4de-297e-419e-b2b3-18b3272f8022","total_cost_usd":1.5681727500000002,"usage":{"input_tokens":24,"cache_creation_input_tokens":64193,"cache_read_input_tokens":1219479,"output_tokens":22218,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":64193,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1,"output_tokens":581,"cache_read_input_tokens":82708,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3